<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Endemic to Bolivia and only known from Yungas cloud forest with secondary vegetation between 2100-2300 m in the ANMI Apolobamba.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">BOLIVIA. La Paz</emphasis>
: Prov. Tamayo, ANMI Apolobamba, camino Pelechuco-Apolo, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H. Huaylla et al.</emphasis>
2754 (MO, OXF).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aristolochiifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea aristolochiifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as apparent from the peculiar placement of the peduncle in the leaf sinus but immediately distinguished by the larger corolla c. 4 cm long (not 1.5-2.5 cm), the pubescent sepals and the larger leaves, pubescent beneath.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
